carte.definition: A bill of fare; a menu.
carte.example1: The seller claimed to be offering classified proprietary information on IOI’s intranet architecture, along with a series of administrative access codes and system exploits that could “give a user carte blanche inside the company network.”
carte.example2: His habitual absence emboldened the more brutal prison officials and gave them carte blanche to do whatever they wanted.
carte.example3: Thus he could fall asleep that night untroubled by the nightmare that he had given Crick carte blanche for another foray into frenzied inconsiderateness.

affix.definition: That which is affixed; an appendage.
affix.example1: A name was written on a scrap of fabric affixed to the crown —James.
affix.example2: The clipped items and slips were turned over to the paster who affixed the clippings to the slips.
affix.example3: After listening to the chief, the magistrate rapidly made out the necessary traveling documents and affixed the official stamp.

wifey.definition: Of, befitting, pertaining to, or characteristic of a wife.

alight.definition: (with from) To get off or exit a vehicle or animal; to descend; to dismount.
alight.example1: Already a flight of four had been seen over the southwest shores of Hosk, not alighting but spying out the sheepfolds, barns, and villages.
alight.example2: Hardly an arm’s length away, he was looking back at her, his face alight.
alight.example3: Thin and tired, hopeful, happy—and hungry, his remarkable face alight with expectation—the old warrier was returning from the wilderness.

clint.definition: The relatively flat part of a limestone pavement between the grikes

sandbag.definition: A sturdy sack filled with sand, generally used in large numbers to make defensive walls against flooding, bullets, or shrapnel.
sandbag.example1: The old lady was heavier now than a pile of sandbags.
sandbag.example2: Finally he lashed a score of sandbags around the basket for ballast.
sandbag.example3: The men spent that first day digging foxholes, filling and stacking sandbags to protect their positions.

unplanned.example1: But compared with Regalia, it looked unplanned, like a place where someone had lined up a bunch of oddly shaped boxes in rows.
unplanned.example2: Herr Becker was referring to the Nazis’ claim that the riots were an unplanned uprising in retaliation for the murder of a high-ranking Nazi official by a Jew.
unplanned.example3: Something unrehearsed, unplanned, was going to happen, and we were going to be made to look bad.

momentous.definition: Outstanding in importance, of great consequence.
momentous.example1: Soon after Hale and Ramsey were convicted, White faced a momentous decision.
momentous.example2: This convenient comparison is given extra poignancy by Beethoven’s reference to the French despot in his momentous third symphony, these days known as the Eroica but originally dubbed the Bonaparte.
momentous.example3: As casual as they strove to seem, they both felt something momentous take shape between them, and—though she didn’t for a minute question his intentions—something intimate, too.

reorder.definition: The process of ordering something again.
reorder.example1: His response to the mounting demands was not to reorder priorities to give his staff and graduate students some breathing space, but to add a late-night shift to keep the cyclotron running around the clock.
reorder.example2: Picture albums, address books, receipt-keeping, these were the happy tasks of people completely staked to one another, so that they could produce a chit on demand, order and reorder their memories for a future day.
reorder.example3: I take the time to reorder my supplies, wad up the sleeping bag, and messily stuff everything into the backpack.

flamboyant.definition: The royal poinciana (Delonix regia), a showy tropical tree.
flamboyant.example1: I had expected someone flamboyant, someone older trying desperately to look young, someone who viewed me as a piece of meat to be prepared for a platter.
flamboyant.example2: It was just as in so many civil rights organizations, he mused: the flamboyant male leaders make the speeches while the workaday women, most of them as plain as bread, make it happen.
flamboyant.example3: She had been imagining the scene of a crime, a Gothic cathedral, whose flamboyant vaulting would be flooded with brazen light of scarlet and indigo from a stained-glass backdrop of lurid suffering.

lingo.definition: Language, especially language peculiar to a particular group, field, or region; jargon or a dialect.
lingo.example1: And if our readers do know the lingo, we might be insulting their intelligence by spelling it out.
lingo.example2: “Tons of things. Hard to remember all the names now, you know. Was speaking the lingo like a native by the time I left.”
lingo.example3: Even when we have an inkling that we are speaking in a specialized lingo, we may be reluctant to slip back into plain speech.

flowering.example1: On May 4 Seabiscuit and War Admiral were brought out on a grassy lawn before a pink flowering hedge to pose for an army of photographers.
flowering.example2: Paths of white stones meandered among flower beds, hedgerows, vegetable gardens, fruit trees, and flowering plants.
flowering.example3: A kind of crocus itself, just before flowering.

ransack.example1: Sasha ransacked their own brain looking for the file, but it didn’t seem to be there.
ransack.example2: The room had been ransacked: drawers were hanging open and books had been tossed all over the place.
ransack.example3: Even in the fading light I could tell the house was a disaster; it looked like it’d been ransacked by thieves.

behemoth.definition: A great and mighty beast God shows Job in Job 40:15–24.
behemoth.example1: They saw no hulking behemoth capable of the enormous sound they had heard.
behemoth.example2: This was especially true of the cases against Conexco—a shadowy behemoth that controlled the rumrunning traffic on the West and Gulf Coasts.
behemoth.example3: Hina meets me at the train station, a squat green glass behemoth that looks too big for a city block.

kerosene.definition: A petroleum-based thin and colorless fuel
kerosene.example1: It had helped her save on kerosene by keeping water hot so she did not have to boil more water every time she needed to mix it with milk powder.
kerosene.example2: They start in hay carts and trash bins; they follow kerosene trails down the center of streets; they turn corners; they enter bashed-in doorways.
kerosene.example3: He ate one of his sandwiches in the second-floor corridor, sitting on a bench with his camera beside him and the can of kerosene on the floor.

faded.definition: To grow weak; to lose strength; to decay; to perish gradually; to wither, as a plant.
faded.example1: Towels, underwear, and faded saris flapped on clotheslines hung across the balconies.
faded.example2: He had on a faded green track suit top and looked about a stone heavier than when I’d last seen him.
faded.example3: The hilltop faded, and Harry stood in Dumbledore’s office, and something was making a terrible sound, like a wounded animal.

impossibility.example1: They seemed to realize the impossibility of touching tar without being defiled.
impossibility.example2: During a car trip to nearby Aurora, they “talked over the impossibility of our union....The reasons we both enumerated very calmly—and they seemed weighty indeed.”
impossibility.example3: I was getting bewildered; he so crowded on my mind his list of nature’s eccentricities and possible impossibilities that my imagination was getting fired.

masseuse.definition: A woman who performs massage; a female masseur.
masseuse.example1: “You offer just one massage? What if you stay on as my personal masseuse for twelve years?”
masseuse.example2: Yet the masseuse paused as her fingertips alighted on my spine.
masseuse.example3: Hospitals pitch birthing centers, day cares pitch love, high schools pitch success ... card dealerships pitch luxury, counselors self-esteem, masseuses happy endings, cemeteries eternal rest ...

Croatian.example1: “We have Croatian deckhands on the ship. They don’t speak our language either, but somehow we communicate.”
Croatian.example2: They had just returned from their summer vacation on the Croatian coast.
Croatian.example3: Will it make a difference if she is Croatian, Muslim, Serbian?

asymmetric.example1: “If there were any way to get asymmetric forces out of that, where you get force in one direction and not the other, you’d get a propulsive force.’
asymmetric.example2: “I wanted the design to be asymmetric and curvy,” he explained.
asymmetric.example3: The Japanese designer came up with his clever but familiar plays on proportions, introducing double-breasted blazers and soft, asymmetric draped bottom halves for women.

axiom.definition: A seemingly self-evident or necessary truth which is based on assumption; a principle or proposition which cannot actually be proved or disproved.
axiom.example1: With so many axioms, all the theorems are surface ones requiring only three or four steps to prove; none has any depth.
axiom.example2: I always remember the regent’s axiom: a leader, he said, is like a shepherd.
axiom.example3: With the feeling that he was speaking to O’Brien, and also that he was setting forth an important axiom, he wrote: Freedom is the freedom to say that two plus two make four.

stagnation.example1: Some of the sick lie without motion, suffering an entire stagnation of the fluids.
stagnation.example2: Even King, the black leader most committed to the traditional path of multiracial coalitions and nonviolence, would soon grow frustrated with the movement’s stagnation.
stagnation.example3: Political and economic stagnation undermined many black Americans’ confidence in the old tactics of the civil rights movement.

manger.definition: A trough for animals to eat from.
manger.example1: Back at the barns, men carry in hay on wooden forks, dump grain in the mangers, and carry out manure.
manger.example2: Pomp hath informed us that at midnight on Christmas Eve, the animals are reputed to speak, as they did around the manger.
manger.example3: Miss Violet reached for Lloyd, but he ducked and disappeared behind one of the cardboard cows by the manger.

sorrowful.definition: (of a person) exhibiting sorrow; dejected; distraught.
sorrowful.example1: He have no right to be talkin’ to his father in that manner on a sorrowful day.
sorrowful.example2: The days grow ever more strained and my mother’s eyes more sorrowful.
sorrowful.example3: “It’s a bad situation,” he said, his voice as soft and sorrowful as an autumn leaf slip-sliding to the ground, “but I’ll let it go.”

concoct.definition: To prepare something by mixing various ingredients, especially to prepare food for cooking.
concoct.example1: Cook’s love and admiration for the queen and her palate moved the broth that she concocted from the level of mere food to a high art.
concoct.example2: Madame Manec’s energy, Marie-Laure is learning, is extraordinary; she burgeons, shoots off stalks, wakes early, works late, concocts bisques without a drop of cream, loaves with less than a cup of flour.
concoct.example3: But one morning she announced that she would wait no more, and the seeds went into the ground that day, followed by biweekly applications of the thick black fertilizer she concocted in the evenings.

bloodthirsty.definition: Thirsty for blood: inexorably violent or eager for bloodshed; murderous.
bloodthirsty.example1: They had been spinning themselves into a frothing, famished frenzy, like bloodthirsty piranhas, in front of our house all morning.
bloodthirsty.example2: I kept staring at the fissure in the marble floor where two years ago Nico had banished a bunch of bloodthirsty skeletons to the Underworld.
bloodthirsty.example3: The posse of bloodthirsty whites still rampaged across the Valentine farm when they left.

endear.definition: To make (something) more precious or valuable.
endear.example1: It was nowhere as blond as Vera Louise’s hair once was, but its sunlight color, its determined curliness, endeared him to her.
endear.example2: It was Zeitoun, and she had no choice but to find it endearing.
endear.example3: Petey watched them go, each of them as bowlegged and as strangely endearing as a toddler.

immersed.definition: To put under the surface of a liquid; to dunk.
immersed.example1: But after playing for a few minutes, I quickly became immersed in the reality created by the words on the screen.
immersed.example2: If we were Baptist or some other denominations, we had been immersed.
immersed.example3: Having been immersed in the development of the atom’s destructive potential, they were hoping to shift as a team into work on the generation of electricity and other such peacetime aspects of the embryonic science.

ripped.definition: To divide or separate the parts of (especially something flimsy such as paper or fabric), by cutting or tearing; to tear off or out by violence.
ripped.example1: Pieces of a sheet of a paper are taped to the door, but someone’s ripped it off so nothing’s left but the corners.
ripped.example2: Her will clamped onto him and his words reeled out as though she’d reached down his throat and ripped them from him.
ripped.example3: A hand clutched at the stirrups, then was ripped away.

tundra.definition: A flat and treeless Arctic biome.
tundra.example1: At first she invented rhymes about the tundra and sang them to tunes she had learned at school.
tundra.example2: We were surrounded by nothing but polar tundra and the Laptev Sea.
tundra.example3: It might have been the gyptians’ sledge dogs, or it might have been wild spirits of the tundra, or even those freed daemons crying for their lost children.

favored.definition: To look upon fondly; to prefer.
favored.example1: Not given an environment that favored the development of intensive agriculture, that is, they shaped the landscape into something more suitable to their purposes.
favored.example2: As population densities rose, food production became increasingly favored because it provided the increased food outputs needed to feed all those people.
favored.example3: Her bare legs and arms were bruised and scraped; one ankle was badly swollen and she favored it, limping to the table where Alys had set a bowl of porridge.

periphery.definition: The outside boundary, parts or surface of something.
periphery.example1: Mr. A. H— moves along the periphery, going mostly unnoticed and speaking with only a few of the other guests, including Mr. Barris, who introduces him to Herr Thiessen.
periphery.example2: “I don’t know,” I say, the possibilities firing in my head, though most of them involve Dennis, and now even Jack, the two of them watching the blaze from the periphery.
periphery.example3: His friend, standing at the periphery, had been listening and now asked me the same thing.

chrysanthemum.definition: Any of many flowering perennial plants, of the genus Chrysanthemum, native to China, that have showy radiate heads.
chrysanthemum.example1: Each emblem contains a chrysanthemum twisted inside the symbol of their high house to represent their relationship to the royal family.
chrysanthemum.example2: When that was done, she picked up a chrysanthemum and studied it closely, turning it this way and that.
chrysanthemum.example3: My mother put hers, a chrysanthemum, below her left breast.

crucifixion.definition: An execution by being nailed or tied to an upright cross and left to hang there until dead.
crucifixion.example1: Like the carvings and stained-glass windows in European cathedrals, the art in San Lorenzo and other Olmec cities consisted mainly of powerful, recurring images—the crucifixions and virgins, so to speak, of ancient Mesoamerica.
crucifixion.example2: Ben was not taking his symbolic crucifixion with any excess humor.
crucifixion.example3: A Child of Our Time intersperses quasi-operatic narrative passages with arrangements of African-American spirituals, as Bach had done with Lutheran hymn-chorales in his oratorios on the passion and crucifixion of Jesus Christ.

kickback.definition: A backward kick, a retrograde movement of an extremity.
kickback.example1: “He was learning to shoot and the kickback hit him in the mouth. Knocked a few of his teeth out.”
kickback.example2: “Now, remember, keep your elbows a little bent and your wrist tight for the kickback. Aim at the can, and when you got it, squeeze the trigger.”
kickback.example3: Companies arranged kickbacks for buying certain products, and a black market in stolen equipment thrived.

flared.example1: When I put them on, the hammer symbol above the knuckles flared bright.
flared.example2: Lord Vdaryon's shining Pride of Driftmark was trying to turn, but the demon ran a lazy green finger across her silvery oars and they flared up like so many tapers.
flared.example3: Its feathers flared bright gold when the lights came on.

normalization.definition: Any process that makes something more normal or regular, which typically means conforming to some regularity or rule, or returning from some state of abnormality.
normalization.example1: After conferring with my colleagues, I felt it necessary to speed up the process of normalization.
normalization.example2: “You help me with this new normalization campaign, and I’ll help you with that paper you almost failed.”
normalization.example3: I’m not sure we understand the implications of that yet, the normalization of killing individuals.

sandstone.definition: A sedimentary rock produced by the consolidation and compaction of sand, cemented with clay etc.
sandstone.example1: There was nothing but the wide expanse of flat desert, which reached toward the edge of the horizon, where massive sandstone plateaus stood that were as faint and round as orange clouds.
sandstone.example2: It was some form of chalky granite, or a sandstone, but imbedded in it were large pieces of a darker stone, a harder and darker stone.
sandstone.example3: Remembering a sandstone ledge I had seen while prowling the woods, I went there.

sensing.definition: To use biological senses: to either see, hear, smell, taste, or feel.
sensing.example1: Without taking his eyes off the girl—her back was turned now and he feasted himself on her rounded jeans —he pondered the meaning of what Howie had said, sensing the importance of the moment.
sensing.example2: Maybe it was the Ring that called to the Wraith-lord, and for a moment he was troubled, sensing some other power within his valley.
sensing.example3: Wab, sensing a dark turn in the tale, tried to cut her off.

tuft.definition: A bunch of feathers, grass or hair, etc., held together at the base.
tuft.example1: Nat pointed at the table a few feet away, and when Jinny glanced down at it, she recognized a lumpy tuft of tangled black hair sticking out from under the tabletop.
tuft.example2: The burro chewed the dry tufts of grass as close to the gray shale as it could and strained against the reins to reach another sparse clump of grass.
tuft.example3: The path was well maintained, though narrow; the dirt was hard packed in the center, and tufts of brown grasses grew along the edges.

ebb.example1: I cannot bring myself to do more than lie there and wait for it to ebb.
ebb.example2: In the ebb of their fortunes, this sum was their total capital; yet they laid it unhesitatingly against Matthewson’s six hundred.
ebb.example3: The power occasionally ebbed due to problems with the generator, so Kemmler’s body would unpredictably slump, then sit upright again, every muscle straining against the straps.

copywriter.definition: A person who writes advertising copy (the text used in advertisements).
copywriter.example1: Their place was only six blocks from where I worked as a copywriter for a small ad agency, so two or three times a week I would drop by after work.
copywriter.example2: I can hardly believe this is a first novel by someone self-described as a bass-player and advertising copywriter, the dumbest jobs in music and writing.
copywriter.example3: What Fin, a midlevel copywriter, does have on Don is a sense of humor, which he often trains on himself.

gravely.definition: In a grave or serious manner.
gravely.example1: “If the Iron Rod has been stolen, it must be found immediately,” he said to them gravely.
gravely.example2: For a long minute the three of them looked at her, Theodora and Luke curiously, the doctor gravely.
gravely.example3: The other lady, who had not spoken yet, said gravely and emphatically, “Very true!”

trucking.definition: To drive a truck: Generally a truck driver's slang.
trucking.example1: His father, who had emigrated at the turn of the century from the city of Odessa in the Ukraine, worked mainly as a trucking clerk, dispatching drivers on their routes.
trucking.example2: Left to himself, Paul, a slight boy with dark hair, spent hours trucking through the patchwork of fields and residences.
trucking.example3: Tony had a GED and had built a successful trucking company in Las Vegas, but it hadn’t survived the recession.

congee.definition: Leave, formal permission for some action, :
congee.example1: Breakfast in South China, at least for those who could afford it, was congee—white rice porridge’with lettuce and dace paste and bamboo shoots.
congee.example2: It's food enough for two paired with a complimentary cup of soup -- a commendable congee on my visit to this attractive art-filled enclave.
congee.example3: “But at the same time, all the old roast duck shops and congee stores will still be there. They’ll just be 10 years older.”

aptly.definition: In an apt or suitable manner; fitly; appropriately
aptly.example1: Anya struggled to find a word that aptly described him now.
aptly.example2: The bridge is aptly named the Salmon Creek Gorge Bridge.
aptly.example3: It does show, as you so aptly say, the question is not black and white.”

foolishly.example1: Afraid this man would hurt her child, my mom foolishly gave him all the money she had in her purse.
foolishly.example2: He blushed, grinned foolishly, and everybody grinned back, loving him.
foolishly.example3: But then Burke foolishly shot his pistol at one of the Aborigines, whereupon the whole group fled.

fission.definition: The process whereby one item splits to become two.
fission.example1: The Hanford plant was based on something else scientists had learned about fission.
fission.example2: They told Einstein about the newest discoveries in fission and explained how uranium might be used to build devastating bombs.
fission.example3: The Allies may have used a very powerful bomb, he said, but not a real atomic bomb, not a bomb based on the fission of uranium atoms.

commemorative.definition: An object made to commemorate a person, mark an event, etc.
commemorative.example1: In November 1942, the commander of the Southern Front turned up to present thirty-two members of the 588th with commemorative watches as a reward for their service, and medals to ten others.
commemorative.example2: We joked about all the commemorative marches and boring speeches we had been spared by leaving this particular weekend.
commemorative.example3: And on a pillow several badly cracked pieces of delicate china, a commemorative plate celebrating the St. Louis World Fair .

liquefy.example1: Then her mother collapsed; she simply began to slide down as if her bones had liquefied until she half lay, half sat on the floor.
liquefy.example2: “Maybe we can save some of it,” he says as he finally grasps the Comet can and pulls it out of the water upside down, dumping even more liquefying powder into the tub.
liquefy.example3: Some of the monkeys were so badly liquefied that she and Trotter didn’t even bother to do a necropsy, they just yanked samples of liver and spleen from the dead animal.

lark.definition: Any of various small, singing passerine birds of the family Alaudidae.
lark.example1: My preference would be to last eternity with you beside me on a cloud, but hell would also be a lark if Westley was with me....
lark.example2: As the nightingales fell silent, the river larks took up their song.
lark.example3: Every morning larks ascend from No Man’s Land.

rudely.example1: I did not want to knock; knocking would intrude rudely on her tears.
rudely.example2: Roger was a funny sort of fellow—kind of gruff, apt to speak bluntly, almost rudely.
rudely.example3: Small, rudely fashioned models of farmhouses and farmyards covered the top of the butte.

ablaze.definition: Burning fiercely; in a blaze; on fire.
ablaze.example1: “This is it!” he yelled, angry, his eyes ablaze, filled with a mixture of venom and fear.
ablaze.example2: Once the candles are all ablaze, the cousins and aunts and children gather around and sing a rousing “Bienvenida a ti,” to the tune of "Happy Birthday."
ablaze.example3: The news shows three patrol cars that have been set ablaze at the police precinct, about a five-minute drive away from us.

fizz.definition: An emission of a rapid stream of bubbles.
fizz.example1: It was so quiet in the hallway, I could hear the bubbles fizzing inside the can.
fizz.example2: With a joyful click, fizz, I open the second can of G&T and realize, with a rush, that I haven’t thought about Tom all day.
fizz.example3: Despite my debilitating shyness, a spark of excitement began to fizz and pop inside me.

rudimentary.definition: (usually in the plural) One of the rudimentary mammae of boars.
rudimentary.example1: One-room cells, with the most rudimentary wooden furniture, housed the inhabitants on the second floor.
rudimentary.example2: It’s a simple notion, almost rudimentary, but accomplishing this in an actual game can be quite difficult.
rudimentary.example3: I was sharing a rudimentary bedroom with Barack, listening to the stereo sound of crickets in the cornfields all around us, the rustle of animals we couldn’t see.

astrological.example1: “Man is often lost in a technological, physiological, astrological lack of logical existence that can best be described as a whole lot of nothing lightly dashed with an obvious hint of Scotch,” Hal says.
astrological.example2: Kepler, reasoning from astrology, dated the moment of transition to 1563: the great planetary conjunction of that year had transformed the world of learning; certainly it had led to a flood of astrological publications.
astrological.example3: For many, the only certainty was the stars, and the ancient astrological conceit prospered in the courtyards and taverns of fear-haunted Europe.

shone.example1: And just then, the late sun must have shone on this side of the building.
shone.example2: Today the house shone so brightly it hurt Hazel’s eyes, and she wondered if it would even allow her in.
shone.example3: He had curried the horses till they shone.

motivator.example1: Hope in the shadow of fear is the world’s most powerful motivator.
motivator.example2: Her letter was a Big Chop that was also a stupendous motivator.
motivator.example3: I believe that economic incentive is crucial as a motivator, especially in a consumer-driven society.

pentagon.definition: A polygon with five sides and five angles.
pentagon.example1: Connecting the corners of that pentagon with lines generates a small, upside-down, five-pointed star, which is exactly the same as the original star in its proportions.
pentagon.example2: His penchant was for textured synthetic fabrics, often featuring some geometric design like diamonds or pentagons.
pentagon.example3: Nestled within the lines of the star is a pentagon.

dissection.example1: The knowledge acquired in dissection had few, if any, practical applications.
dissection.example2: On the day of the earthworm dissection, Justin and I sat in the science lab, staring down at the tray in front of us.
dissection.example3: Carpenter reported his competition’s clients to the police, broke into dissection rooms to mutilate their deliveries.

steppe.definition: The grasslands of Eastern Europe and Asia. Similar to (North American) prairie and (African) savanna.
steppe.example1: While Stalingrad was burning, they were cooling their heels in the fragrant fields of the Russian steppes, surrounded by sagebrush and birdsong.
steppe.example2: “And now, from the steppes of Russia, get ready for the brave Cossacks of the Caucasus!”
steppe.example3: The transformation of warfare by horses began with their domestication around 4000 B.C., in the steppes north of the Black Sea.

adopter.example1: “Some phones are now below $200, encouraging the clever phones to spread beyond corporate users and into early adopters in the consumer market,” the article pointed out.
adopter.example2: Beginning in 1980, the library introduced a computer filing system, and in the 1990s became an early adopter of the Internet.
adopter.example3: As the pandemic took hold, the rescue shelters saw adopters storm their virtual doors.

minuscule.example1: A moment later, an identical package landed in front of Ron, crushing beneath it his minuscule and exhausted owl, Pigwidgeon.
minuscule.example2: But the truly remarkable thing were the tiny ink dots moving around it, each labeled with a name in minuscule writing.
minuscule.example3: Okay, maybe there’s a tiny, minuscule part of me wondering what it would feel like to announce, Ben’s actually the world’s youngest surgeon or Ben’s working in the mayor’s policy office.

basal.example1: “That’s what you call a basal thermometer. It reads the temperature down to a tenth of a degree.”
basal.example2: Bear in mind we are not office workers, sitting around idling at the basal metabolic rate.
basal.example3: My centrioles, basal bodies, and probably a good many other more obscure tiny beings at work inside my cells, each with its own special genome, are as foreign, and as essential, as aphids in anthills.

cured.example1: In Arkansas, where we cured our own meat, we ate halfinch slabs of ham for breakfast, but in St. Louis we bought the paper-thin slices in a strange-smelling German store and ate them in sandwiches.
cured.example2: Although there is some debate about what Edward and William died of, we know that today they would probably have been cured.
cured.example3: He might have fooled you with his angelic face, but I’ve been cured—thoroughly.

wretched.definition: Very miserable; feeling deep affliction or distress.
wretched.example1: Another fellow told me our food was so wretched that he had to flee before it made him sick, so I had his foot cut off, roasted it up, and fed it to him.
wretched.example2: They were wretched, flimsy things, but cooking pots of any kind were always difficult to get.
wretched.example3: “The Crow’s Eye gave him to me, wretched creature that he is.”

amputation.definition: Surgical removal of all or part of a limb, etc.
amputation.example1: Half an hour earlier they had carried out a multiple amputation on a captain from the East Surreys—the regiment the boys in the village had joined.
amputation.example2: In his era, even simple lacerations often left diabetics with savage infections that necessitated limb and digit amputations, a consequence of the disease’s ravaging effect on circulation and immunity.
amputation.example3: Lister worried about the high number of hospital patients who died after undergoing surgeries such as leg amputations or repair of deep knife gashes.

cursing.definition: To place a curse upon (a person or object).

filibuster.example2: The second she gets the floor, it’s like a filibuster—especially when there’s someone new in the group.
filibuster.example3: Russell then organized eighteen Southern Democratic senators in filibustering this bill.4 I thought, This man must be a friend of George Wallace.

crucially.example1: The form of the piece, crucially, was dictated by the story.
crucially.example2: The network included parts of the brain like the anterior cingulate cortex, the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, and, crucially, the prefrontal cortex.
crucially.example3: This assumption was crucially important when it came to trying to understand reproduction.

shockwave.definition: A powerful compression wave produced by the movement of a body through a fluid or gas at a velocity greater than the local speed of sound.

chalet.definition: An alpine style of wooden building with a sloping roof and overhanging eaves.
chalet.example1: Someone has burglarized the chalet of a prominent donor with ties to the Natural History Museum in Paris, and the burglar has been apprehended with a travel case stuffed with gems.
chalet.example2: He created a “memory chalet”—using as his background the layout of the chalet in Switzerland where he stayed on skiing holidays with his parents as a child.

toughen.example1: He said it would toughen up my hands, but it didn't seem to be working.

blimp.definition: An airship constructed with a non-rigid lifting agent container.
blimp.example1: The sky was speckled with puffy silver blimps tethered to the ground by long webs of cable.
blimp.example2: A blimp shines a sky candle over the carriages, and I catch my reflection in the glass again.
blimp.example3: The blimps drop new screens that capture her image.

iterative.definition: (grammar) A verb showing the iterative aspect.
iterative.example1: “Born Pink” is occasionally galvanic, and occasionally iterative.
iterative.example2: “Modernist Cuisine” strapped turbo boosters to the slow, iterative experiments that had been happening in restaurant kitchens, delivering hundreds of ideas, models, and scientific answers on a scale that had been previously unthinkable.

naan.example1: With a very calm and collected look, she explains that we are making a simple chicken curry that could be eaten with rice or naan, or even by itself.

authorized.example1: Some states authorized the family members of the victim to sit at the prosecutor’s table during trial.

fondness.example1: More strongly than my fondness for Pecola, I felt a need for someone to want the black baby to live—just to counteract the universal love of white baby dolls, Shirley Temples, and Maureen Peals.

stealthy.example1: With the absence of Úrsula, with the invisible presence of Melquíades, who continued his stealthy shuffling through the rooms, the house seemed enormous and empty.

shrivel.example1: It was weird to watch his smooth, muscular flesh age, turn a jaundiced yellow, and start shriveling on the bone.

dumbfound.definition: To confuse and bewilder; to leave speechless.
dumbfound.example1: Standing in the barn next to his perfectly sound horse, Smith was dumbfounded.
dumbfound.example2: Jefferson was too dumbfounded to say anything to this tiny sixth-grader with big black glasses and crazy hair getting in his face.

uniformity.example1: But, and it is a big ‘but’, although there are certain cross-cultural uniformities common to all human societies, this doesn’t help us very much, most of the time.
uniformity.example2: The possibility of enforcing not only complete obedience to the will of the State, but complete uniformity of opinion on all subjects, now existed for the first time.

aristocracy.example1: What Adams could never quite fathom, and Jefferson understood intuitively, was that the very word “aristocracy” had become an epithet in the political culture of postrevolutionary America.
aristocracy.example2: These tragic deaths may lead our nation to substitute an aristocracy of character for an aristocracy of color.

flawed.example1: If I could detect a flawed painting so quickly, why had it taken me so long to see the truth about Dr. Lange?

seminal.example1: Pauling’s seminal paper on the protein helix was published in April 1951.

urinal.example1: His honor redeemed by his grandmother’s cans, Estha Alone organized the rusty cans of nothing in front of the urinal.

divination.example1: Once I’d placed the quarter in my inventory, I hadn’t been able to remove it, so I’d never been able to have any divination or identification spells cast on it.
divination.example2: To escape the curse of knowledge, we have to go beyond our own powers of divination.
divination.example3: But there were the butcher priests, too, performing divination of animal entrails, and the Doomsayers on their stilts, crying End Times from behind their skeleton masks.

willfully.definition: Willingly, of one's own free will.
willfully.example1: She was charged with violating section 19 of the Enforcement Act of 1870, which made it illegal for someone to willfully cast an illegal ballot.
willfully.example2: It wasn’t just a matter of ignoring him—it was actively, willfully denying his presence.

orifice.definition: A mouth or aperture, such as of a tube, pipe, etc.; an opening.
orifice.example1: I didn't think I could handle the risk of bleeding out of every orifice in public, even if it meant no longer cursing my reflection.
orifice.example2: “Person A takes a blood-filled appendage and sticks it into a moist orifice.”
orifice.example3: Hemorrhage occurred from all orifices of the body.

gambit.definition: An opening in chess, in which a minor piece or a pawn is sacrificed to gain an advantage.
gambit.example1: Her showdown with John Becker was the kind of gambit that the laboratory expected, encouraged, and valued in its promising male engineers.
gambit.example2: Tristran read it to himself, looking for something about which he could begin to talk: a conversational gambit of some kind—any kind.
gambit.example3: I can’t help but feel that her decision to join us was a gambit of her own.

suspender.example1: He wore suspenders with T-shirts and gave them dirty looks when he was sweeping his sidewalk.
suspender.example2: They had learned to anticipate how he would hook his thumbs behind the tiny black catch buttons of his suspenders.
suspender.example3: Torn pants, grimy jackets, one of the men in suspenders; they do not wear uniforms.

brisk.definition: (often with "up") To make or become lively; to enliven; to animate.
brisk.example1: Ivanito began jumping nervously in place, jumping brisk little jumps like he was trying to stay warm.
brisk.example2: The nurse was about as old as Mrs. Coulter, Lyra guessed, with a brisk, blank, sensible air; she would be able to stitch a wound or change a bandage, but never to tell a story.
brisk.example3: One of the four would open his or her eyes, and from there the movements were brisk, the house quickly growing loud.

caucus.definition: A usually preliminary meeting of party members to nominate candidates for public office or delegates to be sent a nominating convention, or to confer regarding policy.
caucus.example1: "Soooo," Brother Jack said, looking from face to face, "there's been a caucus and decisions have been made. Did you take minutes, Brother Chairman? Have you recorded your wise disputations?"
caucus.example2: Members of both parties cast their votes at precinct-level meetings—caucuses—in the middle of winter, and the whole nation paid attention.

inanimate.example1: The rhythmic sounds might be the recapitulation of something else—an earliest memory, a score for the transformation of inanimate, random matter in chaos into the improbable, ordered dance of living forms.
inanimate.example2: These and other inanimate things she saw and experienced.
inanimate.example3: The residue of the human spirit smeared on inanimate objects was all he could withstand of humanity.

profusely.example1: One had a deep cut across his face and was bleeding profusely.

outlandish.example1: Always so deliberate, hardly surprised by the most outlandish advents.

sampler.definition: A piece of needlework embroidered with a variety of designs.
sampler.example1: Nico explains that the keys are programmed to the sampler of a drum kit he loaded earlier.
sampler.example2: Mother was awakening to the sorry facts: My biscuits were like stones, my samplers askew, my seams like rickrack.

attainable.example1: It didn’t need to be big, but something easily attainable—like my parents had always taught me: one small goal at a time.
attainable.example2: Often he rose early in the morning, before anyone else, and poured himself liquid through the sunrise streets, and everything seemed beautiful, everything in its proper orbit, nothing impossible, the entire world attainable.
attainable.example3: For intellectuals, journalists, and millions of workers, a future without capitalism seemed real and attainable.

printed.definition: To produce one or more copies of a text or image on a surface, especially by machine; often used with out or off: print out, print off.
printed.example1: The two women walk the room and hand out hot-pink folders with the Eighty-First Annual Clover City Miss Teen Blue Bonnet logo printed across the front in gold script.
printed.example2: Then he assured her that no one had given him a bomb to take onto the plane, and she, in return, gave him a printed boarding pass.
printed.example3: She seized a quill pen and printed two lines on a scrap of the curly birch bark which the children collected to use in place of costly paper.

turbocharge.definition: To increase the power of (an internal combustion engine, either Otto or Diesel cycle) by compressing the inlet air with power extracted from the exhaust air.

reblog.definition: The reposting of something previously posted on another blog.

apologizing.definition: (often followed by “for”) To make an apology or excuse; to acknowledge some fault or offense, with expression of regret for it, by way of amends
apologizing.example1: Not only was Victoria Lyons apologizing to me, but she was also inviting me to a party?
apologizing.example2: "Sorry," said Tristran, not entirely sure what he was apologizing for.
apologizing.example3: Helene shoves past the gate guards toward the Commandant's house, apologizing to a group of Yearlings when she knocks two of them over.

soulless.definition: As if without a soul; insensitive, unfeeling.
soulless.example1: He stood once more and again in his high flat house without sides to it and without a roof with his soulless sword standing upright in his hand.
soulless.example2: Charles recalled too clearly the cruelty of his Efik captors, taunting him and his father, telling them that the white men had sharp teeth and purchased slaves to eat them soulless.
soulless.example3: Despite her prayers, the Congo was left in the hands of soulless, empty men.

iffy.definition: Of dubious authenticity, legitimacy or legality.
iffy.example1: They were only lukewarm about his prospects, eyeing that iffy left foreleg and pronouncing the horse only “serviceably useful.”
iffy.example2: “It’s getting to the point where folks can’t step outside the Thicket without one of us gods escorting them. Even then it can get iffy.”

familial.definition: Of or pertaining to a human family.

kindest.definition: Having a benevolent, courteous, friendly, generous, gentle, liberal, sympathetic, or warm-hearted nature or disposition, marked by consideration for – and service to – others.
kindest.example1: He was at his kindest and most genial, setting the woman at her ease.

disloyal.example1: I did not expect her to know that the flowers were symbols of faithlessness, and that with my gift I rebuked her for being disloyal.

doppelganger.example3: A month later, I was on a bus in Hackney when a friend told me there was a new video online of my doppelganger.

sinkhole.definition: A hole formed in soluble rock by the action of water, serving to conduct surface water to an underground passage
sinkhole.example1: The Tangerine Times printed a special pullout section on the Lake Windsor Middle School sinkhole.
sinkhole.example2: The reason this sinkhole had done such massive damage to the school was that all the portables were connected by wooden walkways.
sinkhole.example3: The engineers condemned everything “within a hundred-yard radius of the focal point of the sinkhole,” which was right under Portable 19.

subliminal.definition: (of a stimulus) Below the threshold of conscious perception, especially if still able to produce a response.
subliminal.example1: They won’t buy a television, like everyone else, because my father says it turns you into a cretin and emits harmful radiation and subliminal messages as well.
subliminal.example2: What is most interesting about this page is a subliminal impression created by an accident in its design.
subliminal.example3: Every nightmare that shook every sleeper in Weep carried the same subliminal warning.

moratorium.definition: An authorization to a debtor, permitting temporary suspension of payments.
moratorium.example1: Abolitionists were becoming hopeful that more profound death penalty reform or possibly a moratorium might be achievable.
moratorium.example2: As it happened, not everyone in the nuclear research and development community thought a test moratorium would be a bad thing.

feta.definition: A variety of curd cheese made from sheep’s or goat’s milk and originating from Greece.
feta.example1: He substituted feta cheese for the yak cheese in the recipe because yak cheese is very hard to come by, even in Manhattan.
feta.example2: I was actually pretty good at finding ways to turn the vegetarian ground beef, beets, feta cheese, and apricots into something edible.

hilly.definition: (of a landscape) Abundant in hills; having many hills.
hilly.example1: Then it clattered on down the hilly road.
hilly.example2: If God had any justice, I thought, tromping up and down the hilly road, he would answer my prayers for Mr. Zielinski.
hilly.example3: He had been in the same place for thirty years: a shop at the top of a hilly street where few customers passed.

forestry.definition: The science of planting and growing trees in forests.
forestry.example1: There was some legal jargon, but I grasped this: She committed J.T. and Digger to the custody of juvenile services—to nine months in a forestry camp for juvenile offenders out in western Maryland.
forestry.example2: Replanting through an immediate tree nursery and forestry program is being urged in communities that are losing large numbers of elms.
forestry.example3: I wonder if they’re actually cutting down trees and sleeping in tents at that forestry camp.

procrastinating.definition: To delay taking action; to wait until later.
procrastinating.example1: “Sure thing, Slinkey. I’ll send out three lieutenants this afternoon to get the job done. There’s no sense in procrastinating any longer.”
procrastinating.example2: I would think I was procrastinating, when in reality, I was memorizing the geography of the world.
procrastinating.example3: “As you can see, that leaves almost no time for brooding, lagging, plodding, or procrastinating, and if we stopped to think or laugh, we’d never get nothing done.”

quotient.definition: The number resulting from the division of one number by another.
quotient.example1: I like school, anyway, which increases the loser quotient above and beyond what most other kids would calculate, simply based on the whole two-years-younger-than-my-classmates thing.
quotient.example2: I can’t help but be a little intrigued by his unknown quotient.
quotient.example3: She was planning to publish a paper about the effects of Dad’s teaching methods on our intelligence quotients.

shrinkage.definition: The act of shrinking, or the proportion by which something shrinks.

shrinkage.example2: They found that 16 of the proteins were associated with brain shrinkage either in mild cognitive impairment or Alzheimer's.
shrinkage.example3: But isn’t it possible that this shrinkage is better thought of as a winnowing, as we zero in on those friendships that are actually reciprocated?

phenotype.definition: The appearance of an organism based on a multifactorial combination of genetic traits and environmental factors, especially used in pedigrees.
phenotype.example1: When a severe selection pressure is applied—a rise in temperature or a sharp restriction of nutrients—organisms with the “fittest” phenotype are selected.
phenotype.example2: Galton had proposed using physical and mental traits—human phenotype—to select the best specimens for breeding.
phenotype.example3: Eugenicists such as Galton had hoped to select complex phenotypes—intelligence, height, beauty, and moral rectitude—as a biological shortcut to enrich genes for intelligence, height, beauty, and morality.

multi-purpose.definition: Designed or intended to fit more than one type of function or application; having multiple uses.

multimeter.definition: An electronic measuring instrument that combines multiple functions; a combined voltmeter, ammeter and ohmmeter.

aria.definition: A musical piece written typically for a solo voice with orchestral accompaniment in an opera or cantata.

aria.example2: I just have to find some way to make it as entertaining as a cello solo, an operatic aria, or a magic trick.
aria.example3: In each case, the dreaded clicker sounded after a minute or two, before the contestant had reached the middle of the aria.

chivalry.example1: The chivalry of the Old Ones fought their way from the ruined encampment, hand to hand.
chivalry.example2: “Courage, honor, integrity, and chivalry,” Coach murmurs when we finish fencing.
chivalry.example3: Near all the chivalry of the south had come to Renly's call, it seemed.

capturing.definition: To take control of; to seize by force or stratagem.
capturing.example1: But what if Byrne, in capturing Bobby’s queen, wound up in a weakened position that left him less able to attack the rest of Bobby’s forces and less able to protect his own?
capturing.example2: I turn in time to catch Rufus snapping a photo of me; capturing moments really is his thing.
capturing.example3: He wants to make more portraits again; he decides he’s most passionate about capturing people.

crooked.definition: To bend, or form into a hook.
crooked.example1: Our hiking boots land on the crooked planks with hollow thumps.
crooked.example2: She wore pajamas, a rough brown sweater buttoned crooked, and a big apron, not a work apron but a bib.
crooked.example3: He smiled, showing a mouth full of crooked yellow teeth.

laxative.definition: Any substance, such as a food or in the form of a medicine which has a laxative effect.
laxative.example1: Take a laxative, such as prunes, and eat nourishing food.
laxative.example2: Most jockeys ingested every manner of laxative to purge their systems of food and water.
laxative.example3: It was no wonder the main medicines of this era were laxatives.

elapse.definition: (of time) To pass or move by.

biotech.example1: We pass a sign for a biotech company.
biotech.example2: But plenty of science was already on hold while researchers, universities, and biotech companies sued one another over ownership of various cell lines.

accuser.definition: One who accuses; one who brings a charge of crime or fault.
accuser.example1: Second show would be when school-closing bell rang and the little black face had to look out at her accusers again.
accuser.example2: Even her cousin Lancel, who once had claimed to love her, was one of her accusers.
accuser.example3: “I cannot believe that a fellow scythe would show such cowardice. I demand that the accuser reveal his or herself.”

indemnify.definition: To secure against loss or damage; to insure.
indemnify.example1: And yes, there were precautions administrators took to indemnify themselves against all eventualities.
indemnify.example2: At the Academy, we’d found out that this phrase was basically a legal requirement that you shouted out to indemnify yourself when you were, for whatever reason, applying a bit of extra force.
indemnify.example3: The client signs a contract indemnifying V.A.S. of, among other things, injury and death.

lucifer.definition: A self-igniting match, ie. one which could be lit by striking on any surface (as opposed to safety matches which only light against the material on the side of the box).
lucifer.example1: When that wind blew, the simplest of devices—from lucifer matches to lantern-slides—would no longer function.
lucifer.example2: “The lucifer on the sofa is me,” says Daniel.
lucifer.example3: She also tweeted that the "devil, satan, lucifer, the serpent that deceived Eve, the father of all liars, should be taking lying lessons from Mike Pence."

spandex.definition: A synthetic fibre known for its exceptional elasticity.

spandex.example2: It's a swarm of spandex pants, water bottles fixed to sports belts, and numbered bibs.
spandex.example3: In the second room was either Dana’s mother or Dana himself, wearing red spandex pants and a ratty wig.

coldly.definition: In a cold or uncaring manner; indifferently.
coldly.example1: “And it’s not for you,” she added coldly.
coldly.example2: With supplies shrinking and his men dropping, Cornwallis coldly started to force many refugees out of the town.
coldly.example3: “I would by no means suspend any pleasure of yours,” he coldly replied.

gild.definition: To cover with a thin layer of gold; to cover with gold leaf.
gild.example1: One critic praises not only the show but the entresol itself, admiring the lack of “high class decor,” no plush drapes or gilded cornices, as in the rest of the gallery.
gild.example2: Heavy draperies with brocade and tassels hang on the windows and separate the rooms; paintings in gilded frames hang close together on the walls.
gild.example3: He slipped inside the tent, leaving Griff to contemplate the gilded skull of his old friend.

ovulation.definition: The release of an ovum from an ovary.
ovulation.example1: Twenty-four hours after the deed, my mother’s body temperature rose another two tenths, confirming ovulation.
ovulation.example2: These super cows were injected with hormones to increase ovulation drastically and cause the production of multiple embryos.
ovulation.example3: The implant halts ovulation and gives hens' reproductive system a break.

reliever.example1: I open my own medipak, nowhere near as good as hers, but there’s white tabs in it that I know are at least pain relievers, however cruddy and homemade.
reliever.example2: When they finally got home, Grandma had no sooner sent Ernie upstairs—with the beer bottle containing the half tooth—to lie down with a double dose of pain reliever when the phone rang.
reliever.example3: Because willow bark contains salicylic acid, a pain reliever.

heyday.definition: A period of success, popularity, or power; prime.
heyday.example1: Even during the heyday of Rome, the Romans were not exactly math whizzes.
heyday.example2: Strabo offers the best surviving description of the city in its heyday.
heyday.example3: During what we may call my heyday, I preached much more often than that.

boldness.definition: The state of being bold; courage.
boldness.example1: He was disappointed, but not inclined to believe Yossarian, for he had been given a sign, a secret, enigmatic vision that he still lacked the boldness to divulge.
boldness.example2: In a very short time, because of his skill and his boldness of body and mind, he became the first man of Vitellozzo’s troops.
boldness.example3: “I know a human could stand the sight of me,” she had said, blazing with a boldness Minya had never seen.

fifteenth.definition: The person or thing in the fifteenth position.
fifteenth.example1: It was the week after his fifteenth birthday.
fifteenth.example2: By the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries, landlords in central and Southern China had an almost completely hands-off relationship with their tenants: they would collect a fixed rent and let farmers go about their business.

icicle.definition: A drooping, tapering shape of ice.

pec.definition: (usually in the plural) The pectoralis major muscle.

glob.definition: A round, shapeless or amorphous lump, as of a semisolid substance.

remand.definition: The act of sending an accused person back into custody whilst awaiting trial.
remand.example1: He was led away to be locked in Martin’s museum—in what used to be the sacristy and was now the island’s makeshift jail cell—until he could be remanded to police on the mainland.
remand.example2: Bram Fischer stood up and asked the court for a remand on the grounds that the defense had not had time to prepare its case.
remand.example3: At 8:30 I appeared before the local magistrate and was formally remanded to Johannesburg.

tambourine.definition: A percussion instrument consisting of a small, usually wooden, hoop closed on one side with a drum frame and featuring jingling metal disks on the tread; it is most often held in the hand and shaken rhythmically; by extension, any frame drum.
tambourine.example1: He paused, watching a girl with a tambourine twirling dizzily on the lawn.
tambourine.example2: He hands it off to Dill’s mother, who sips it like it’s lemonade, passes it on, and goes back to beating her tambourine.
tambourine.example3: Deborah, singing and beating her tambourine in the front of the congregation, watched him.

distillation.definition: The act of falling in drops, or the act of pouring out in drops.
distillation.example1: The expertise at distillation that medieval Islamic alchemists developed to produce alcohols and perfumes also let them distill petroleum into fractions, some of which proved to be even more powerful incendiaries.

empowered.definition: To give permission, power, or the legal right to do something.

solenoid.definition: A coil of wire that acts as a magnet when an electric current flows through it.

subsystem.definition: A group of related components that are part of a larger system.

reorganization.definition: The act or process of rearranging. See reorganize.
reorganization.example1: Both the House and Senate Intelligence Committees "introduced bills calling for sweeping reorganization of the entire intelligence apparatus of the government."

reorganization.example3: If what you mean is, Mom reorganized my closet brilliantly, don’t water it down by saying, Moms reorganization of my closet was brilliant.

fanboy.definition: A male fan who is obsessive about a particular subject (especially, something or someone in popular entertainment media).

inflection.definition: (grammar) A change in the form of a word that reflects a change in grammatical function.

isp.definition: Any species known only from trace fossils, such as footprints, coprolites or nests.

refundable.example1: Nevertheless, the game generated a treasure-hunt excitement, and presently he, too, succumbed to the fun, the fervor of this quest for refundable empties.

remittance.definition: The act of transmitting money, bills, etc. to a distant place, in return or payment for goods purchased.

planar.example1: It was composed of dazzling blue metal with an almost mirror shine to it, as smooth as water, and nowhere rectilinear or planar, but all flowing contours, as supple as skin.
planar.example2: It is one of the most beautiful sights in the show — with a subtly planar structure seems implicitly modern.

prospectus.definition: A document, distributed to prospective members, investors, buyers or participants, which describes an institution (such as a university), a publication or a business and what it has to offer.
prospectus.example1: In the prospectus filed last week, investors were cautioned about the potential risks of investing in Poly Culture, which was formed around 2000.
prospectus.example2: The new service also underlines one way Twitter’s monetary power can be measured; as the New York Times , the prospectus for Twitter’s upcoming IPO contains dozens of mentions of TV.

unchanging.definition: To revert or reverse a change
unchanging.example1: Though the Semitic biblical cosmos toppled the Aristotelian one, the idea of an eternal, unchanging universe was not expunged completely, enduring even to the twentieth century.
unchanging.example2: He described all the ways the Library was suited for the blind—the routine, the unchanging furniture, the textured knobs and cupboards in the kitchen.
unchanging.example3: Her face remained unchanging and sad, and her eyes remained haunted by the sorrow of Neewo’s loss.

rump.definition: The hindquarters of a four-legged mammal, not including its legs
rump.example1: The tweed trousers billowed around Ignatius’ gargantuan rump as he rolled forward.
rump.example2: He gathered his hind legs underneath him and lowered his rump, ready to jump.
rump.example3: Long years of practice and usage had made her rump an unusually versatile and dexterous thing.

imperialist.example1: Another Peking, China paper, Jenmin Jihpao, said that the death showed that “in dealing with imperialist oppressors, violence must be met with violence. ”
imperialist.example2: While mesmerized by the beauty of the area, I was constantly rebuked by the buildings and streets that bear the names of white imperialists who suppressed the very people whose names belonged there.

loony.definition: An insane or very foolish person.
loony.example1: “Every loony in New York comes out of the woodwork on nights like this,” the regular beat cop had warned her.

loony.example3: But then again, I’m already in the loony bin; how practical am I going to get?

weaponize.example1: When I realized who he was, my heart rose and fell and I considered going back inside before that flaming marshmallow could be weaponized.

snowboarding.example1: He hates snowboarders, he says, but I think he really means that he hates people who have families who take them snowboarding.
snowboarding.example2: Three boys tell him all about snowboarding; a few girls draw curlicue hearts in their notebooks.
snowboarding.example3: Even so, it’s not every national leader who writes about his tattoos, or his time in the boxing ring, or snowboarding.

engross.definition: To write (a document) in large, aesthetic, and legible lettering; to make a finalized copy of.
engross.example1: She’s taciturn, but so am I. Is she waiting for me to start something, reveal myself, or is she a believer, engrossed in inner meditation?
engross.example2: I gasped, then pretended I was engrossed in the book.
engross.example3: Zu gave us an apologetic shrug before tugging Hina away, back to the circle of younger kids who were engrossed in some kind of card game.

glug.definition: The sound made when a significant amount of liquid is poured suddenly out of something, such as a jug or bottle.
glug.example1: I glugged down the pop I’d been swishing around in my mouth and said, “No, sir.”
glug.example2: On the tragic day, I came home, said hi to Mom, glugged down some milk, and headed down to the basement to practice.
glug.example3: There’s an aquarium next to me, water glugging noisily through its filter.

dismount.definition: The part of a routine in which the gymnast detaches from an apparatus.
dismount.example1: There was no groom at the stable to help her dismount.
dismount.example2: All around him other people were dismounting from brooms and, in two cases, skeletal, black winged horses.
dismount.example3: After Woolf dismounted, Azucar butted him out of the way, ran over a spectator, slashed the NBC Radio wire—cutting off the national broadcast—and dragged his terrified groom down the track like a toboggan.

swinging.definition: To rotate about an off-centre fixed point.
swinging.example1: Hazel was at his back, swinging her sword at any monster that came close, but there were too many swarming around them—at least a dozen.
swinging.example2: It was not their fault that they were young and cheerful, he reminded himself as he carried the swinging beam of his flashlight back through the darkness.
swinging.example3: Five seconds later, a pair of feet dangled next to her, then jerked back up, the beam of David’s flashlight swinging around drunkenly.

vandal.definition: A person who needlessly destroys, defaces, or damages other people's property.
vandal.example1: The Mother Paula’s vandal was finally in custody, so there was no reason to spend the night on guard at the trailer.
vandal.example2: The idea was to send an unambiguous message to the vandals themselves.
vandal.example3: “Do you think the vandals are in my hometown?”

fortitude.definition: Mental or emotional strength that enables courage in the face of adversity.
fortitude.example1: There simply wasn’t enough time to summon either fortitude or fear.
fortitude.example2: Here is a task for all that a man has of fortitude and delicacy.’”
fortitude.example3: Then I stand up, force fortitude to my legs, and begin negotiations.

complicit.definition: Associated with or participating in an activity, especially one of a questionable nature.
complicit.example1: “Hamas! Terrorism! Is Iran complicit? Talking points will be on the board! Have fun!”
complicit.example2: “And you truly feel that Ms. Rachpaul and her young child were complicit?”
complicit.example3: She and Shin’s brother were the ones who had been complicit in starting a chain of events that resulted in his arrest, torture, and hazing in secondary school.

inappropriately.example1: He was without social unease—inappropriately so, in the view of many.

inappropriately.example3: “Mom, Uncle Stanley is behaving inappropriately,” I said.

racking.definition: To place in or hang on a rack.
racking.example1: I told them whatever I could, racking my brain for nuggets of twentieth-century history from Mrs. Johnston’s class—the moon landing! the Berlin Wall!
racking.example2: He wobbled away on his bicycle, the cigarette dangling from his mouth, the cough racking his body.
racking.example3: My father began to cough again, the deep, dry, racking cough that shook his frail body and frightened me terribly.

legalization.definition: The process of making something legal, the process to legalize, decriminalization.
legalization.example1: I didn't care if we were supposedly nearing the end of our legalization nightmare.
legalization.example2: We were always supposedly nearing the end of our legalization nightmare.
legalization.example3: To be sure, the legalization of abortion in the United States had myriad consequences.

sulfuric.definition: Of, or relating to sulfur, especially in its higher oxidation state
sulfuric.example1: The clouds of Venus turn out to be chiefly a concentrated solution of sulfuric acid.
sulfuric.example2: However, the surface of the planet is a scorching 467 degrees Celsius, the ground is barren and rocky, and clouds of sulfuric acid roam the atmosphere.
sulfuric.example3: It is always raining sulfuric acid on Venus, all over the planet, and not a drop ever reaches the surface.

punter.definition: One who bets (punts) against the bank.
punter.example1: It was safe to say I was a terrible punter, and after a little while, Wello told me it would be better if I stopped.
punter.example2: “I don’t want to be anywhere near the upper mountain when those punters are up there,” he seethed.
punter.example3: The average punter at a slickly produced West End musical might not know the name, but Complicite's influence can be found on the most mainstream of stages.

sax.example1: I put my sax case back next to the bed and was about to leave the room when I looked over at Herman E. Calloway’s back.
sax.example2: He would play John Coltrane—type solos on his sax for hours and be dressed in a winter jacket and gym shorts the whole time.
sax.example3: When Richie was fourteen he’d grown from a tittering, cackling torturer of me to a handsome, slick high school kid who was an outstanding tenor sax player.

posing.definition: To place in an attitude or fixed position, for the sake of effect.
posing.example1: “This wight worked as an oral surgeon. It wouldn’t surprise me to learn that the skull he’s posing with belonged to one of his peculiar victims.”
posing.example2: They got out and walked toward the temple, posing first for pictures by the pair of lions that flanked the steps.
posing.example3: It was a picture of the Duncan Dancers, Isadora Duncan’s daughters, posing very theatrically in long white tunics.

popularly.example1: But in this context it merely meant that the National Party would be part of any popularly elected government provided it polled enough votes.
popularly.example2: We were soon transferred to the Johannesburg Prison, popularly known as the Fort, a bleak, castle-like structure located on a hill in the heart of the city.
popularly.example3: What broke loose is popularly and succinctly described as hell.

socioeconomic.definition: Of or pertaining to social and economic factors.
socioeconomic.example1: In the 1968 election, race eclipsed class as the organizing principle of American politics, and by 1972, attitudes on racial issues rather than socioeconomic status were the primary determinant of voters’ political self-identification.
socioeconomic.example2: In my eyes, one of the biggest blessings was that the campaign crossed all socioeconomic, religious, political, racial, gender, and age boundaries.
socioeconomic.example3: No. Studies consistently indicate that drug markets, like American society generally, reflect our nation’s racial and socioeconomic boundaries.

videographer.definition: Any person involved in the production of video material, but especially a person who uses a video camera.

ejection.example1: An ejection seat is simply the aluminum seat the pilot sits in, with a small rocket motor built into the back of it.
ejection.example2: Under Bratton, the number of ejections from subway stations — for drunkenness, or improper behavior — tripled within his first few months in office.
ejection.example3: “Stay in line! Stay in line! Leaving the line will result in your ejection!”

redistribution.definition: The act of changing the distribution of resources.
redistribution.example1: Since as hunter-gatherers they did not produce crop surpluses available for redistribution or storage, they could not support and feed nonhunting craft specialists, armies, bureaucrats, and chiefs.
redistribution.example2: Societies with effective conflict resolution, sound decision making, and harmonious economic redistribution can develop better technology, concentrate their military power, seize larger and more productive territories, and crush autonomous smaller societies one by one.
redistribution.example3: Amalgamation, centralized conflict resolution, decision making, economic redistribution, and kleptocratic religion don’t just develop automatically through a Rousseauesque social contract.

oxidative.definition: Of, relating to, or produced by oxidation.
oxidative.example1: Matter changes hands, atoms flow in and out, molecules pivot, proteins stitch together, mitochondria send out their oxidative dictates; we begin as a microscopic electrical swarm.
oxidative.example2: At the interior of our cells, driving them, providing the oxidative energy that sends us out for the improvement of each shining day, are the mitochondria, and in a strict sense they are not ours.
oxidative.example3: It is now known that the mitochondria are tiny packets of enzymes, a varied assortment including all the enzymes necessary for the oxidative cycle, arranged in precise and orderly array on walls and partitions.

sulfide.definition: Any compound of sulfur and a metal or other electropositive element or group.
sulfide.example1: “Well, not technically allergic, but they give me digestive issues that, um...You know like when tiny amounts of hydrogen, carbon dioxide, and methane combine with hydrogen sulfide and ammonia in the large intestine?”
sulfide.example2: The first primitive forms of life consumed various materials, including hydrogen sulfide, and released oxygen.
sulfide.example3: We mix together and spark the gases of the primitive Earth: hydrogen, water, ammonia, methane, hydrogen sulfide—all present, incidentally, on the planet Jupiter today and throughout the Cosmos.

hydrangea.definition: Any of several shrubs, of the genus Hydrangea, having large clusters of white, pink or blue flowers
hydrangea.example1: A foremost authority on prairie flora and fauna, she could discuss at length the thirty-seven varieties of hydrangea in Crawford County.
hydrangea.example2: She took an active interest, for example, in Nick’s flower garden, often eating the heads off the daffodils and hydrangeas, also off the lilacs and roses when those plants bloomed.

dusting.example1: Almost before we even started, mochiko flour got everywhere, dusting the kitchen.

dusting.example3: I was supposed to be sweeping and dusting.

hydra.definition: Any of several small freshwater polyps of the genus Hydra and related genera, having a naked cylindrical body and an oral opening surrounded by tentacles.
hydra.example1: His palm was moist and hot as a hydra’s swamp.
hydra.example2: If Percy attacked the giant, the hydra would ravage the city.
hydra.example3: There were miniature lions, pigs, dragons, hydras, even a teeny Minotaur in a little Minotaur diaper.

flunk.definition: Of a student, to fail a class; to not pass.
flunk.example1: I could see fine off in the distance, but up close I flunked—just barely.
flunk.example2: A student could flunk every weekly test as well as the final exam and still pass a course for that period.
flunk.example3: But then in my annual checkup in October I flunked the audiology test and the doctor was like, “Dude, it’s time.”

tempest.definition: A storm, especially one with severe winds.
tempest.example1: I hated these emotional outbursts, these tempests of passion, for they always left me tense and weak.
tempest.example2: When I walked into Camp Four, six Sherpas were struggling to erect Hall’s tents in a 50-knot tempest.
tempest.example3: The air swirls in a tempest around them, blowing open the glass doors to the garden with a tangle of billowing curtains.

reconfigure.definition: To arrange into a new configuration.

millisecond.definition: One one-thousandth of a second. Symbol: ms.
millisecond.example1: This all happened real fast—in milliseconds—and at the same time, I was bringing my gun up.
millisecond.example2: “The Phoenix Riders manage to hang on to victory by a millisecond!” the announcer shouts.
millisecond.example3: Their bodies were a map of cells, a thousand equations, solved by the second, by the millisecond, and she knew only answers.

slept.definition: To rest in a state of reduced consciousness.
slept.example1: I had slept a short while, a diluted sleep that had brought no rest and no dreams.
slept.example2: They used two airfields at the same time: one, the home field, was the place where they ate and slept and took care of their aircraft.
slept.example3: While I’d slept the clouds had blown away, and now the moon lit the surrounding countryside in pale silver light.

padre.example1: But before the padre had got to the end of it, he broke down altogether and sobbed out, “Oh, please your ladyship. 1 beg your pardon, but I have forgotten to keep my tilings.”

tenement.definition: A building that is rented to multiple tenants, especially a low-rent, run-down one.

loiter.example1: Descriptions of the red car’s occupants, provided by witnesses who had noticed them loitering in the area where Otto Ziegler’s body was discovered, had been circulated through the Midwest and Western states.

subgroup.definition: A group within a larger group; a group whose members are some, but not all, of the members of a larger group.
subgroup.example1: Next come crops whose names are consistent only among the languages falling within a small subgroup of those southern Nigerian languages.

impunity.example1: That was the period when divine good humor and the hidden forces of human nature acted with impunity to provoke a state of emergency and upheaval in the laws of physics and logic.

playroom.definition: A room, allocated as a children's play area, in which noisy or boisterous activities are tolerated.
playroom.example1: She stops in the doorway of what I assume is the twins' playroom; two rocking horses sit in the corner, and child-size shelves are lined with books and toys.

wrinkly.example1: She twirls her pasta, dabs the corners of her wrinkly mouth with a red napkin.

enthrall.definition: To hold spellbound; to bewitch, charm or captivate.
enthrall.example1: Even now, having been tortured and imprisoned by Voldemort, the idea of the Dark wizard in possession of this wand seemed to enthrall him as much as it repulsed him.
enthrall.example2: This is the proto-modernity that would eventually enthrall Manet and the other Spain-smitten Frenchmen who forged Modern painting in the 1860s.

circadian.definition: Of, relating to, or showing rhythmic behaviour with a period of 24 hours; especially of a biological process

sweeper.definition: One who sweeps floors or chimneys.

discovering.definition: To find or learn something for the first time.

clearest.definition: To remove obstructions, impediments or other unwanted items from.

echelon.definition: A level or rank in an organization, profession, or society.

kneading.definition: To work and press into a mass, usually with the hands; especially, to work, as by repeated pressure with the knuckles, into a well mixed mass, the materials of bread, cake, etc.
